issue_comment_body:
Hi,
I am developer of rlabplus, for which I have implemented SEP. I have had similar problem, which in my case occured in extract function, when noise matrix was provided but 
  im.noise_type = SEP_NOISE_NONE;
  thresh_type = SEP_THRESH_ABS; 

What I think is the solution is that freeing the pointer cdscan is not done right. In line 743 of the version 1.0.0 of the file extract.c, additional check has to be implemented before freeing cdscan:

l.743: if ((cdscan != NULL) && (cdscan != dummyscan) && (cdscan != dbuf.midline))
l.744:   free(cdscan);

Hope this helps,
Marijan

> name of the compiler executable;
`nagfor`
> I assume it uses the -c flag to compile without link, but if not, please tell me the correct switch;
that's correct
> flag to tell where compiled module objects (.mod) are placed, e.g. in GNU fortran it is -J, in Intel 
> fortran it is -module for example;
flag is `-mdir`
> name (if any) of the MPI version of the compiler, otherwise mpif90 is generally set;
It doesn't come with an MPI implementation but it works with OpenMPI. OpenMPI does have command `mpif90`
> flag (if any) to enable OpenMP directives, e.g. in GNU fortran it is -fopenmp;
flag is `-openmp`
> flag (if any) to enbale CAF, e.g. in GNU fortran it is -fcoarray;
flag is `-num_images=N` where N is the number of images. N is set to 1, i.e. no parallelism. It only recognises coarray syntax. 
> flags (compile and link, if any) to enebale coverage, e.g. in GNU fortran they are [-ftest-coverage 
> -fprofile-arcs, -fprofile-arcs];
NAG compiler does not have this feature.
> flags (compile and link, if any) to enable profile, e.g. in GNU fortran they are [-pg, -pg].
flag is `-pg`

Let me know if you need any further information.

Hi @facetoe , thanks for the quick reply. Unfortunately I had a large job I was doing, and already completed it before seeing your solution. The workaround I used was something like this:
```
def wrapped_zenpy_call(zenpy_call, *args, **kwargs):
    count = 0
    while count < 10:
        try:
            return zenpy_call(*args, **kwargs)
        except requests.exceptions.ConnectionError:
            print "Connection error {}.".format(count)
            if count < 10:
                count += 1
            else:
                raise
```
I never had a call fail more than once in a row, so anything using retries would probably work. Unfortunately I can't run my job again and test your solution.

Thanks!

