I resolved my issue by importing a function that returns a new instance of pyrebase.initialize_app() app, and not initializing it once and using that connection throughout my app which was what i did previously. This solved the successive permission denied errors that required me to restart my app. This may mean that the connection expires.

I still get occasional permission denied errors that I suspect is caused by database locking. But it no longer is the "cause of death".

@teodorgarzdin @bazookon @jayhuang75

Using SQLAlchemy association is one way to achieve what you want. You can define those like:

```python
class Parent(Model):
    ...
    children = orm.relation('Child', secondary=Association.__table__)

# OR

class Parent(Model):
    ...
    _children = orm.relation('Association')
    children = association_proxy('_children', 'child')
```

If you want more control over getters/setters/expression, you can use [hybrd_property](http://docs.sqlalchemy.org/en/latest/orm/extensions/hybrid.html):

```python
class Parent(Model):
    ...
    _children = orm.relation('Association')

    @hybrid_property
    def children(self):
        return self._children

    @children.setter
    def children(self, values):
        self._children = [Association(child=value) for value in values]

    @children.expression
    def children(self):
        return Child
```

