@ilanschnell I just realized I didn't address `conda update conda`.  My goal would be `conda update conda` is translated to `conda update --system conda` unless the environment has a version of `conda` installed into it (something the user already had to override to get there).

When a user runs `conda update conda` and its translated it should display a warning to them that they're using a deprecated command and tell them the new command.  Eventually, once we are ready to release 4.0 and break backwards compatibility, we can remove it all together.

If the user runs `conda update conda` and the environment has `conda` installed in it, they would get the normal warning about it being a system package and prompting them to either type `conda update --system conda` or `conda update conda --override`.  Just like any other system package in an environment that doesn't accept them.

:+1: from me (as one would hope).  @bryevdv and the Bokeh team are using these quite successfully.  Using the wiki provides a clear way to document the outcome of new feature discussions along with a history of all of its changes without having to read through a full issue discussion.

