Ok, I took a look at the conda source. It looks like an NFS delay-related race condition, where one cluster job tries to create a symlink after a symlink from a second cluster job has appeared between the existence check and symlink creation in the first job. The function responsible was [more basic](https://github.com/conda/conda/blob/4.0.10/conda/install.py#L414) in conda v4.0.10  than the symlink function [in v4.2.9](https://github.com/conda/conda/blob/4.2.9/conda/install.py#L535) (it didn't try to remove the symlink if it already exists), but that's not the real issue here. The exception handler in the 4.2.9 version that that would ordinarily ignore such errors is susceptible to the same race condition.  (`os.path.lexists(prefix_file)` may not be True in the exception handler, so the exception gets raised and the activate/deactivate script dies)

If we can patch [`conda/install.py`](https://github.com/conda/conda/blob/master/conda/install.py#L174) to something like the following I believe it should hopefully resolve the issue:

``` python
def symlink_conda_hlp(prefix, root_dir, where, symlink_fn):
    scripts = ["conda", "activate", "deactivate"]
    prefix_where = join(prefix, where)
    if not isdir(prefix_where):
        os.makedirs(prefix_where)
    for f in scripts:
        root_file = join(root_dir, where, f)
        prefix_file = join(prefix_where, f)
        try:
            # try to kill stale links if they exist
            if os.path.lexists(prefix_file):
                rm_rf(prefix_file)
            # if they're in use, they won't be killed.  Skip making new symlink.
            if not os.path.lexists(prefix_file):
                symlink_fn(root_file, prefix_file)
        except (IOError, OSError) as e:
            if (os.path.lexists(prefix_file) and
                    (e.errno in (errno.EPERM, errno.EACCES, errno.EROFS, errno.EEXIST))):
                log.debug("Cannot symlink {0} to {1}. Ignoring since link already exists."
                          .format(root_file, prefix_file))
            elif (e.errno == errno.ENOENT):
                log.debug("Problem with symlink management {0} {1}. File may have been removed by another concurrent process." .format(root_file, prefix_file))
            elif (e.errno == errno.EEXIST)):
                log.debug("Problem with symlink management {0} {1}. File may have been created by another concurrent process." .format(root_file, prefix_file))
            else:
                raise
```

With this change conda should chug along if it can't create the symlink during activation, and it should still work since _one_ of the cluster jobs will have created it. There's a chance there'll be a new race condition if something tries to use the link before NFS can propagate it, but hopefully that will be much less likely.

Thoughts? Anyone care to try this out on their system with a newer version of conda? If it is working for others I can open a PR.

